bug.short_desc: Characters with macrons (Āā Īī Ōō Ūū) do not appear in Mac OS X when the font is set to Georgia

assigned_to.name: Nobody; OK to take it and work on it

long_desc.thetext:
User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; U; Intel Mac OS X 10.5; en-US; rv:1.9.2.8) Gecko/20100722 Firefox/3.6.8 Build Identifier: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; U; Intel Mac OS X 10.5; en-US; rv:1.9.2.8) Gecko/20100722 Firefox/3.6.8
When the font is set to Georgia, characters with macrons (Āā Īī Ōō Ūū) fall back to the next font in the stack. This is expected behavior if the font does not contain macrons. But Georgia does contain them. I don't have access to enough macs to narrow down whether it's a system issue or a firefox issue.
Reproducible: Always
Steps to Reproduce: 1. With a mac, navigate to a page that contains macrons http://jsfiddle.net/JJ64z/ 2. If the characters with macrons are a different font, you've replicated the issue
Actual Results: Characters with macrons appeared as a different font than the one set.
Expected Results: Characters with macrons should appear as the same font that it is set to. Georgia does contain the characters with macrons.
A lot of New Zealand place names and words contain macrons. Few system fonts on both Mac and PC contain characters with macrons, so many New Zealand websites use the font Georgia.
Other applications in OSX have access to Georgia's characters with macrons.
I can't replicate this in Windows.

Created attachment 524100 Screenshot from version 3.6.8 (Mac OS X)
This screenshot (of this page http://jsfiddle.net/JJ64z/) shows the characters with macrons swapping from Georgia to the next font in the font stack (cursive).

What version of the Georgia font do you have installed? You can determine this by looking at it in Font Book; use the Show Font Info (Cmd-I) command to see details of the font version and the actual file being used.
I wonder if this is another manifestation of the peculiar OS X cmap-munging discussed in bug 554820.

(In reply to comment #2) > What version of the Georgia font do you have installed? You can determine this > by looking at it in Font Book; use the Show Font Info (Cmd-I) command to see > details of the font version and the actual file being used.
V5.00x is installed. But I noticed there was a duplicate. It appears Microsoft Office installs Version 2.05 of the font. Somehow the Mac System font is classed as the duplicate. By disabling the earlier, Microsoft installed version it has solved the problem.
Microsoft Office on Mac is to blame for this issue. See Comment 4 for details. This is now resolved.
